-- Oil Options Volatility Rises as Futures Hit 7-Week High
-- B y   C h r i s t i n e   H a r v e y
-- 2013-05-20T20:32:07Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-05-20/oil-options-volatility-rises-as-futures-hit-7-week-high.html
Crude oil options volatility rose as
the underlying futures rallied to a seven-week high.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
July, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a gauge
of options prices, was 20.82 percent at 3:45 p.m. on the  New
York Mercantile Exchange , up from 20.62 May 17.  West Texas Intermediate crude for June delivery gained 69
cents to $96.71 a barrel on the Nymex, the highest settlement
since April 2. It was the fourth straight gain.  The most-active options in electronic trading today were
July $90 puts, which dropped 9 cents to 57 cents a barrel on
volume of 7,386 contracts at 3:43 p.m. in New York. July $100
calls were the second-most active, rising 12 cents to 91 cents a
barrel as 4,023 lots changed hands.  Puts made up 53 percent of volume in electronic trading
today. They made up 57 percent of the previous sessionâ€™s volume
of 125,966 contracts.  July $100 calls were the most-active options traded in the
previous session on May 17, with 6,232 contracts changing hands.
They increased 6 cents to 79 cents a barrel. July $90 puts
slipped 17 cents to 66 cents a barrel on volume of 5,700 lots.  Open interest was highest for December $105 calls with
38,019 contracts. Next were July $90 puts with 37,382 lots and
July $110 calls with 34,156.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information the next business day on open-outcry volume, where the bulk of options activity occurs.  To contact the reporter on this story:
